e conservators. He also investigates the inhabitants' social practices from the standpoints of household and kin group, political association, neighborhood, gender ideology, and the effects of these on attitudes toward home ownership. In the face of modernity, where tradition is an object of both reverence and commercialism, Rethemnos emerges as an important ethnographic window onto the ambiguous cultural fortunes of Greece.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aFortezza.  aKhania.  aMacedonia.  aMuslims.  aNew Town.  aPASOK.  aPiraeus.  aThessaloniki.  aactors, social.  aagnatic ideology.  aambiguity.  aapprentices.  abankruptcy.  abargaining.  aboardinghouses.  acapital.  acheating.  adamp.  ademolition.  adowry.  aeconomic history.  aelections.  aengineers, civil.  afavoritism.  agambling.  agossip.  aharbor.  aheritage.  ahistoric conservation.  ahospitality.  aidentity.  ainheritance.  ajewelers.  ajudges.  akinship.  alitigation.  amarriage.  amemory.  amerchants.  anewspapers.  anostalgia.  aotherness.  apolice.  apoverty.  aprecision.  areciprocity.  arhetoric.  asecrecy.  asupermarkets.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400843312zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400843312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400843312.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru